<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="375" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1046,2045]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1225,1252]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Description.</emphasis>
Length: 4 to 4.15 mm, weakly pigmented, anophtalmous, with a pholoeuonid body shape (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1395,1420]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,190,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,179,1367]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Halbherria daffneri n. sp. 1, habitus of holotype. 2, mesoventral process. Figures 3–8. Protibiae et protarsi. 3, H. zorzii. 4, Neobathyscia mancinii. 5, Sphaerobathyscia hoffmanni. 6, Bathysciotes khevenhuelleri. 7, Albanella zoufali. 8, Speonesiotes remyi. Scale bar is 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2653420/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1046,2045]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
Head elongated, with a strong and dense puncture. Antenna approximately 0.57 times as long as the body length, inserted on the first third of the length of the head. Second antennomere longer than the first one. The 1st to 6th and 8th antennomeres cylindrical, the 7th and 9th to 11th conical (regularly widened from base to apex). The approximate length of the antennomeres of the 
<typeStatus box="[683,781,1406,1432]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">holotype</typeStatus>
are, in micrometers: 38, 41, 38, 38, 35, 35, 38, 24, 36, 33, 43. Maxillary palpi wide, the apical segment conical, slightly shorter than the preapical one.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1046,2045]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
Pronotum transverse, 1.5 times (male) or 1.4 times (female) wider than long, the sides convex in the anterior half part, concave in the posterior half, sinuated in the middle (
<figureCitation box="[855,921,1514,1540]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1395,1420]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,190,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,179,1367]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Halbherria daffneri n. sp. 1, habitus of holotype. 2, mesoventral process. Figures 3–8. Protibiae et protarsi. 3, H. zorzii. 4, Neobathyscia mancinii. 5, Sphaerobathyscia hoffmanni. 6, Bathysciotes khevenhuelleri. 7, Albanella zoufali. 8, Speonesiotes remyi. Scale bar is 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2653420/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), the posterior angles significantly protruding outward. Puncture of the pronotum strong and dense, similar to that of the head, lying on a microreticulate background, with no transverse alignment.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1046,2045]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
Elytra 1.5 times longer than wide, independantly rounded at the apex, without sutural stria. Elytral punctation strong and foveolated (
<figureCitation box="[409,492,1657,1684]" captionStart="FIGURES 43–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1619,1644]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,179,1586]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,179,1591]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 43–48. Elytral surface. 43, Halbherria zorzii. 44, Aphaotus jureceki. 45, H. daffneri. 46, Sinuicollia dalpiazi. 47, Lessiniella trevisioli. 48, Sphaerobathyscia hoffmanni. ss=sutural stria, scale bar is 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2653426/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
), always associated with erect setae, not coalescent into transversal strigae, and with microreticulation between dots.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1046,2045]" box="[199,1308,1730,1757]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
Mesoventral process moderately high, with a keen ventral edge, bearing long ventral setae (
<figureCitation box="[1225,1295,1730,1756]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1395,1420]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,190,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,179,1367]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Halbherria daffneri n. sp. 1, habitus of holotype. 2, mesoventral process. Figures 3–8. Protibiae et protarsi. 3, H. zorzii. 4, Neobathyscia mancinii. 5, Sphaerobathyscia hoffmanni. 6, Bathysciotes khevenhuelleri. 7, Albanella zoufali. 8, Speonesiotes remyi. Scale bar is 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2653420/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1046,2045]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Legs slender. Protarsi four segmented and undilated in both sexes, mesotarsi and metatarsi five segmented and undilated in both sexes. Protibiae with a lateral row of irregular spines. Mesotibiae and metatibiae without an apical comb of spines. Onychium with two interongular setae.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1046,2045]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
Aedeagus with a trifid median lobe (in dorsal view), the two lateral branches significantly shorter and more slender than the median branch (
<figureCitation box="[524,594,1910,1936]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–27" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1785,1810]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,187,1751]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[183,1404,179,1758]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9–27. Male genital morphology. 9, Halbherria daffneri n. sp. aedeagus dorsal. 10, H. daffneri n. sp., aedeagus, tip of paramere. 11, H. daffneri n. sp. aedeagus lateral. 12, H. zorzii aedeagus dorsal. 13, H. zorzii aedeagus lateral. 14, H. tamaninii aedeagus dorsal. 15, H. tamaninii aedeagus lateral. 16, Sinuicollia dalpiazi, aedeagus dorsal. 17, S. dalpiazi, aedeagus lateral. 18, Speonesiotes muelleri. aedeagus dorsal. 19, Speonesiotes muelleri, aedeagus lateral. 20, Albanella scutariensis aedeagus dorsal. 21, Albanella scutariensis, aedeagus lateral. 22, Redensekia likana, aedeagus dorsal. 23, Aphaotus jureceki, aedeagus dorsal. 24, Neobathyscia mancinii, genital segment. 25, H. zorzii, genital segment. 26, Aphaotus jureceki, genital segment. 27, Bathysciotes khevenhuelleri, genital segment. Scale bar is 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2653422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Median lobe angulate in the middle, then thickened in lateral view (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 9–27" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1785,1810]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,187,1751]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[183,1404,179,1758]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9–27. Male genital morphology. 9, Halbherria daffneri n. sp. aedeagus dorsal. 10, H. daffneri n. sp., aedeagus, tip of paramere. 11, H. daffneri n. sp. aedeagus lateral. 12, H. zorzii aedeagus dorsal. 13, H. zorzii aedeagus lateral. 14, H. tamaninii aedeagus dorsal. 15, H. tamaninii aedeagus lateral. 16, Sinuicollia dalpiazi, aedeagus dorsal. 17, S. dalpiazi, aedeagus lateral. 18, Speonesiotes muelleri. aedeagus dorsal. 19, Speonesiotes muelleri, aedeagus lateral. 20, Albanella scutariensis aedeagus dorsal. 21, Albanella scutariensis, aedeagus lateral. 22, Redensekia likana, aedeagus dorsal. 23, Aphaotus jureceki, aedeagus dorsal. 24, Neobathyscia mancinii, genital segment. 25, H. zorzii, genital segment. 26, Aphaotus jureceki, genital segment. 27, Bathysciotes khevenhuelleri, genital segment. Scale bar is 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2653422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Parameres thin, regularly arcuate, as long as the median lobe, with three apical setae extended partly beyond the apex of the median lobe, the external seta inserted slightly behind the two others (
<figureCitation box="[1101,1184,1982,2008]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–27" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1785,1810]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,187,1751]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[183,1404,179,1758]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9–27. Male genital morphology. 9, Halbherria daffneri n. sp. aedeagus dorsal. 10, H. daffneri n. sp., aedeagus, tip of paramere. 11, H. daffneri n. sp. aedeagus lateral. 12, H. zorzii aedeagus dorsal. 13, H. zorzii aedeagus lateral. 14, H. tamaninii aedeagus dorsal. 15, H. tamaninii aedeagus lateral. 16, Sinuicollia dalpiazi, aedeagus dorsal. 17, S. dalpiazi, aedeagus lateral. 18, Speonesiotes muelleri. aedeagus dorsal. 19, Speonesiotes muelleri, aedeagus lateral. 20, Albanella scutariensis aedeagus dorsal. 21, Albanella scutariensis, aedeagus lateral. 22, Redensekia likana, aedeagus dorsal. 23, Aphaotus jureceki, aedeagus dorsal. 24, Neobathyscia mancinii, genital segment. 25, H. zorzii, genital segment. 26, Aphaotus jureceki, genital segment. 27, Bathysciotes khevenhuelleri, genital segment. Scale bar is 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2653422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Endophallus without basal sclerites, with two symmetric lateral longitudinal narrow lamellae in the medio-apical region (
<figureCitation box="[1270,1338,2018,2044]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–27" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1785,1810]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,187,1751]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[183,1404,179,1758]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9–27. Male genital morphology. 9, Halbherria daffneri n. sp. aedeagus dorsal. 10, H. daffneri n. sp., aedeagus, tip of paramere. 11, H. daffneri n. sp. aedeagus lateral. 12, H. zorzii aedeagus dorsal. 13, H. zorzii aedeagus lateral. 14, H. tamaninii aedeagus dorsal. 15, H. tamaninii aedeagus lateral. 16, Sinuicollia dalpiazi, aedeagus dorsal. 17, S. dalpiazi, aedeagus lateral. 18, Speonesiotes muelleri. aedeagus dorsal. 19, Speonesiotes muelleri, aedeagus lateral. 20, Albanella scutariensis aedeagus dorsal. 21, Albanella scutariensis, aedeagus lateral. 22, Redensekia likana, aedeagus dorsal. 23, Aphaotus jureceki, aedeagus dorsal. 24, Neobathyscia mancinii, genital segment. 25, H. zorzii, genital segment. 26, Aphaotus jureceki, genital segment. 27, Bathysciotes khevenhuelleri, genital segment. Scale bar is 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2653422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
