<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="377" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1924,2024]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1436,153,287]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="377" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1924,1951]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species is recorded from two caves of the high altitude karst system of Piani Eterni in southern Dolomitic mountain range, in the Dolomiti Bellunesi national park (Italian Alps) where it occurs along with 
<taxonomicName authority="Paoletti" authorityName="Paoletti" box="[151,464,1997,2023]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Sinuicollia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dalpiazi">
<emphasis box="[151,369,1997,2023]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Sinuicollia dalpiazi</emphasis>
Paoletti
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Daffner, 1992" authorityName="Daffner" authorityYear="1992" box="[522,894,1997,2023]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Orotrechus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grottoi">
<emphasis box="[522,729,1997,2023]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Orotrechus grottoi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Daffner, H." box="[736,894,1997,2023]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" pagination="85 - 90" refId="ref4980" refString="Daffner, H. (1992) Orotrechus grottoi sp. n. aus Norditalien, Veneto (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Trechinae). Nachrichtenblatt der Bayerischen Entomologen, 41 (3), 85 - 90." type="journal article" year="1992">Daffner, 1992</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. This karst system is one of the deepest in north- ern 
<collectingCountry box="[196,247,153,179]" name="Italy" pageId="10" pageNumber="377">Italy</collectingCountry>
reaching a depth of more than 
<quantity box="[611,701,153,179]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="377" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000 m</quantity>
. Its karstologic and tectonic characteristics were investigated by Sauro 
<emphasis box="[226,284,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="377">et al.</emphasis>
(2013) and the groundwater fauna is reviewed in 
<bibRefCitation author="Sambugar, B. &amp; Ferrarese, U. &amp; Martinez-Ansemil, E. &amp; Stoch, F. &amp; Tomasin, G. &amp; Zullini, A." box="[863,1131,189,215]" pageId="10" pageNumber="377" pagination="67 - 76" refId="ref6055" refString="Sambugar, B., Ferrarese, U., Martinez-Ansemil, E., Stoch, F., Tomasin, G. &amp; Zullini, A. (2008) The groundwater fauna of Piani Eterni karstic area (Dolomiti Bellunesi National Park, Southern Limestone Alps, Italy) and its zoogeographic significance. Subterranean Biology, 6, 67 - 76." type="journal article" year="2008">
Sambugar 
<emphasis box="[986,1045,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="377">et al.</emphasis>
(2008)
</bibRefCitation>
. This locality significantly extends the distribution area of 
<taxonomicName box="[504,630,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Halbherria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[504,630,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="377">Halbherria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
towards the north (
<figureCitation box="[847,932,225,252]" captionStart="FIGURE 60" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1858,1883]" captionTargetBox="[190,1398,180,1828]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[190,1398,179,1830]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 60. Geographical and altitudinal distribution of species of the Italian genera of Bathysciotina (except Sphaerobathyscia). Detailed distribution are given for the species of Aphaotus, Halbherria, Sinuicollia and Lessiniella, only geographical global limits of the distribution area is given for the genus Neobathyscia. For coherence, graphical codes are the same as in Giachino &amp; Vailati, 2005 and Vailati, 2017, supplemented with the data of the genera Lessiniella and Sinuicollia (with agreement of the authors)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2653432/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="377">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
). No information is available about the depth and the conditions in which the species has been collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
